solution.text:
Wavelength of monochromatic green light
$$
\begin{aligned}
&=5.5 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~cm} \\
&\text { Intensity I }=\frac{\text { Power }}{\text { Area }} \\
&=\frac{100 \times(3 / 100)}{4 \pi(5)^2} \\
&=\frac{3}{100 \pi} \mathrm{Wm}^{-2}
\end{aligned}
$$
Now, half of this intensity (I) belongs to electric field and half of that to magnetic field, therefore,
$$
\begin{aligned}
&\frac{\mathrm{I}}{2}=\frac{1}{4} \varepsilon_0 \mathrm{E}_0^2 \mathrm{C} \\
&\text { or } \mathrm{E}_0=\sqrt{\frac{2 \mathrm{I}}{\varepsilon_0 \mathrm{C}}}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
&=\sqrt{\frac{2 \times\left(\frac{3}{100} \pi\right)}{\left(\frac{1}{4 \pi \times 9 \times 10^9}\right) \times\left(3 \times 10^8\right.}} \\
&=\sqrt{\frac{6}{25} \times 30}=\sqrt{7.2} \\
&\therefore \mathrm{E}_0=2.68 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{m}
\end{aligned}
$$
